SIMPLE: triumphant
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Triumphant
<hw>Tri*um"phant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>triumphans</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>triumphare</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>triomphant</ets>. See <er>Triumph</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Rejoicing for victory; triumphing;
exultant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Successful beyond hope to lead ye forth⟦br⟧
<qex>Triumphant</qex> out of this infernal pit.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Celebrating victory; expressive of joy for success;
<as>as, a <ex>triumphant</ex> song or ode</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Graced with conquest; victorious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Athena, war's <qex>triumphant</qex> maid.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So shall it be in the church <qex>triumphant</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Perkins.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to triumph; triumphal.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Captives bound to a <qex>triumphant</qex> car.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Church triumphant</b></col>, <cd>the church in heaven,
enjoying a state of triumph, her warfare with evil being over; --
distinguished from <contr>church militant</contr>. See under
<er>Militant</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Triumphantly</ent>⟦br⟧
